# What measures has the Ukrainian government taken to protect its critical infrastructure and power sources from Russian attacks?

## Summary
The Ukrainian government has taken numerous steps to protect its critical infrastructure and power sources from Russian attacks <font color=#FF3399>[1]</font>. Emergency power outages and restrictions to limit electricity use were put in place across Ukraine <font color=#FF3399>[2]</font>, while the G7 also established a "coordination mechanism" to aid in repairs <font color=#FF3399>[3]</font>. Sergei Kovalenko, CEO of Yasno, reported a 32% deficit in projected power supply on Monday <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>. 500 power generators were sent to Ukraine from 17 EU countries to help ease the crisis <font color=#FF3399>[4]</font>, while Ukrainian Air Force spokesperson Yuriy Ihnat stated that Russia was likely stockpiling missiles and drones for future strikes <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy estimated that around 40% of the country's energy infrastructure had been seriously damaged <font color=#FF3399>[5]</font>.

## Claims
| Claim Sentence | Context |
|---|---|
|<font color=#FF3399>[1]</font> Rolling power cuts were introduced to save energy while engineers carry out repairs.<a href="https://www.dw.com/en/ukraine-power-outages-become-a-daily-reality/video-63619441" target="_blank">Source</a>| Russian airstrikes have seriously damaged more than a third of Ukraine's energy infrastructure. Many Ukrainians are without electricity or water supplies. Rolling power cuts were introduced to save energy while engineers carry out repairs.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[2]</font> Emergency power outages and restrictions to limit electricity use were put in place across Ukraine on Thursday, according to national energy company Ukrenergo, amid Russia's attacks against critical infrastructure.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-11-03-22/h_0efbbd42a0a231ea179aed27b97f6bec" target="_blank">Source</a>| Emergency power outages and restrictions to limit electricity use were put in place across Ukraine on Thursday, according to national energy company Ukrenergo, amid Russia's attacks against critical infrastructure. Ukrenergo added that the restrictions were in place to balance Ukraine's power system, following repeated attacks on its grids by Russian missiles and drones.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[3]</font> The G7 has established a "coordination mechanism" to help Ukraine "repair, restore and defend its critical energy and water infrastructure," the group's foreign ministers said in a joint statement on Friday following meetings in Mnster.<a href="https://www.cnn.com/europe/live-news/russia-ukraine-war-news-11-04-22/h_c385d6702ae33392504bd3ccdb00d096" target="_blank">Source</a>| The G7 has established a "coordination mechanism" to help Ukraine "repair, restore and defend its critical energy and water infrastructure," the group's foreign ministers said in a joint statement on Friday following meetings in Mnster. The statement condemned Russia's attacks against civilians and civilian infrastructure, "in particular energy and water facilities" in Ukraine.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[4]</font> Ukraines authorities have issued scheduled blackouts across the country in order to stabilise the grid, and 17 EU countries have sent 500 power generators to Ukraine to help ease the energy crisis.<a href="https://www.theguardian.com/world/2022/nov/07/ukraine-occupied-kherson-loses-power-as-kyiv-mayor-urges-residents-to-prepare-for-total-blackouts" target="_blank">Source</a>| Sergei Kovalenko, CEO of Yasno, a major supplier of energy to the capital, said Ukraine faced a 32% deficit in projected power supply on Monday. "This is a lot, and its force majeure," he said. Ukraines authorities have issued scheduled blackouts across the country in order to stabilise the grid, and 17 EU countries have sent 500 power generators to Ukraine to help ease the energy crisis. "Probably, there will be no light in Beryslav until the city is completely de-occupied," he said in a Telegram update on Sunday night.|
|<font color=#FF3399>[5]</font> Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy said that around 40% of the country's energy infrastructure has been seriously damaged.<a href="https://www.foxnews.com/health/ukraines-power-outages-russian-air-strikes-pose-challenge-critically-ill" target="_blank">Source</a>| "It's a war and there's nothing we can do about it," 65-year-old Halytska said from her hospital bed. Russia stepped up attacks on power plants, substations and other targets in mid-October amid numerous battlefield setbacks following its Feb. 24 invasion. Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskiy said that around 40% of the country's energy infrastructure has been seriously damaged. On Thursday, Ukrainian Air Force spokesperson Yuriy Ihnat said on television that Russia was likely stockpiling missiles and drones for future strikes.|
